Chapter 15: The Gut
The "Gut" was a vertical maintenance shaft that ran the length of the Academy’s foundation, a labyrinth of rusted pipes and coolant vents that smelled of sulfur and dead air. Here, the school’s waste—both physical and energetic—trickled down into the deep earth.
"Stay close to the pipes," Hobs whispered, his mechanical arm hissing as he pivoted on a narrow iron catwalk. "The Association doesn't monitor the heat signatures here. They think the Void-rot is too thick for anything to survive."
[Warning: High Toxicity Environment]
[Atmospheric Integrity: 14%]
[Entropy Sight: Active]
Ren looked at the massive conduits surrounding them. They weren't just carrying water; they were pulsing with a sickly, violet sludge—spent Essence, the byproduct of hundreds of students channeling powers at once.
"The school is bleeding," Ren muttered. Through his silver-and-black vision, he could see the [Degradation Timers] on the pipes. Some were flickering in the seconds.
"It’s not bleeding," Hobs replied, his iron hand gripping a ladder. "It's being drained. The Academy acts like a filter. It takes the raw, chaotic energy of the kids and 'refines' it for the Board. You’re looking at the runoff."
"Ren!" Mira gasped. She was clinging to a railing, her staff glowing a panicked, frantic white. "Look down."
Below them, in the darkness of the shaft, something was moving. It wasn't a Void-creature. It was a mass of discarded, broken Academy drones—the ones Ren had seen destroyed in Training Hall 4—all fused together into a jagged, metallic centipede. It had no eyes, only a sensor-array that emitted a clicking sound like a broken Geiger counter.
[Target: Scavenger-Sentinel (Corrupted)]
[Status: Logic Loop detected]
[Action: Avoid or Deconstruct?]
"It’s a 'Scrapyard Guard'," Hobs hissed, freezing against the wall. "If it pings us, the whole shaft goes into lockdown."
The metallic centipede climbed the wall with a rhythmic, clanking sound, its sensor-array scanning the catwalk just inches from Ren’s boots.
[Entropy Sight: Identifying Critical Node...]
[Target: Central Processing Core (Located at the base of the neck)]
[Timer: 00:00:05 until Detection]
Ren didn't wait. He didn't have his 'Logic Blade'—he didn't have the Mana for it—but he had the Mark. He reached out, his hand trembling with the cold weight of the Void, and touched the vibrating metal of the Sentinel’s spine.
"Delete," he whispered.
He didn't erase the whole machine. He focused on a single, tiny line of code: the 'Detection' command.
[Skill Trigger: Structural Deconstruction (Minor)]
[Logic Altered: 'If Target = Human' -> 'If Target = Shadow']
The Sentinel’s clicking stopped. The sensor-array swept over Ren, then Mira, and finally Hobs. It paused, the red eye flickering to a dull, neutral green. It perceived them not as intruders, but as part of the darkness. It continued its climb, clanking harmlessly past them toward the upper levels.
"You... you just rewrote a Sentinel in mid-air," Mira whispered, her face pale.
"I didn't rewrite it," Ren said, his hand feeling numb. "I just gave it a reason to ignore us."
"Keep moving," Hobs urged, though he looked at Ren with a new, wary respect. "We're almost at the Sub-Vault entrance. The 'Gate' is right behind the next pressure seal."
As they reached the final door—a massive, circular hatch marked with a faded [PROJECT ARCHITECT] logo—the humming Ren had heard in the basement returned. It was louder now, a physical vibration that made the marrow in his bones feel like it was boiling.
[Warning: Proximity to the 'Dormant Gate' is destabilizing your Local Cache.]
[Sync Rate: 92%... 94%...]
"This is as far as I go," Hobs said, his mechanical arm locking into a socket on the wall to act as a manual brace. "I’ll hold the seal open. Once you’re in the Sub-Vault, you’re off the map. Not even the Association can see you there."
"Ren," Mira said, gripping her staff. "If the 'Black Box' is there, what do we do once we find it?"
Ren looked at the hatch. His vision was filled with silver and violet static. The 'Administrator' was no longer just a voice; it was a presence, waiting just behind the metal.
"We rewrite the detonator," Ren said.
He placed his marked hand on the hatch. The silver geometry on his skin flared, and the massive gears of the Sub-Vault began to turn.
They have reached the heart of the Academy. The final secrets of 'Project Architect' are within reach.
